@kimsim8750 You don't  even know the actual the definition of the term racist.  A person can be any color and be racist.  Racism doesn't just describe whites with negative opinions of other races.  There are numerous people of all races who are racists.  It's just not reported because it doesn't support a particular narrative. Even whites can be the victims of racism.. Plus, as I observed, the term has been used so incorrectly  so often that the word has basically become meaningless.  It merely means in most cases "I don't like you."

 The word racism should be a serious word, however, it has lost all gravitas.  People are called racists and they yawn at the absurb claim.  Also, people like yourself have been deliberately misinformed and miseducated on the actual definition of the word.  Certain "social warriors" deliberately warped the meaning of the word to manipulate young people and the culture to promote their particular agendas.  If I were you, I would start checking out other terms and words that have  been cynically and deliberately distorted or changed to manipulate me and my friends to fulfill someone else's agenda The word racism is just one example that this has been done to.  There has been a widespread  deliberate campaign to corrupt language to support certain ideas.

You are free to accept those ideas, of course..  However, I myself don't like to be manipulated by others no matter the reasons.   I prefer to get the facts and make up my own mind.  However, someone is not trying to persuade people to adopt their beliefs.  They are stacking the deck, so to speak, so people will agree with them without realizing they are being subtly and deliberately manipulated through the use of language.   Have a good Fourth.  Pax..

@skyhunter2816 I agree sharing is often a possibility, but... not always. And I rather doubt it is when it comes to military-level tech (weapons and armor and such). First, it's too valuable, but more importantly... governments aren't going to like that sort of thing being in individual hands, they prefer dealing with corporations. Remember the earlier Iron Man movies they tried to get his tech under their control, and he was able to stop it mainly because he had the money to pay the lawyers to fight it.

As for selling off a small part of it, depends on what she sells. One of the big issues here is that getting a bunch of money requires selling off something significant. A better servo isn't going to lead to a multi-million dollar contract, they're just not worth that much. So I'm struggling to figure out what part she could sell that wouldn't be hugely problematic if everyone else also had them (which is what would happen if it's sold to a corporation). Had Tony Stark needed to sell his rocket system (for flight), his ability to fly wouldn't be so impressive at that point, as soon _everyone_ with some money behind them (or the ability to steal) would be flying, too. That's the minimal sort of thing I could see her selling that would get the sorts of money needed to fund her work.

If she were good at finance too (no reason to think she would be, but hey), she could sell something minor (like the servos) and then get into the stock market and make a bunch.
